Public procurement of construction services and corruption prevention
Joint report by the Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) on their parallel audits
Introduction and overview
The award of services by public authorities is of great importance to both the state and the economy.
The state has the task of using public funds as economically and economically as possible, as well as ensuring fair and regulated competition.
In the European Union (EU), the award of services by public authorities is an important part of the creation of a single economic area.
In order to ensure that competition is largely unrestricted across borders, public authorities must comply with EU rules when awarding contracts above certain value limits (thresholds).
To this end, EU member states must transpose and apply the EU's public procurement law into national law.
This has already happened in both the Czech Republic and Germany.
Below the EU thresholds, it is up to individual countries to regulate the award of public contracts themselves.
The award of services is also an area at risk of corruption.
Due to the generally high potential for damage, the contracting authorities must therefore take appropriate measures to prevent and prevent corruption and undue favours when awarding their contracts.
The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) agreed in January 2011 to carry out parallel audits both for the award of construction services across the EU and for the prevention of corruption.
The audits focused on the application of EU public procurement law, which has been transposed into national legislation, as well as the prevention of corruption in the awarding of construction services in construction, road construction and transport infrastructure.
The awards below the EU thresholds have also been included in the discussions with a view to preventing corruption.
The audit results of both auditors are summarised in this joint report.
The report will also be addressed to international bodies, such as the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI).
The evaluations of the Federal Audit Office on the topics listed are mainly based on cross-sectional tests carried out in 2011 / 2012 by the building authorities, which are responsible for the road and construction of the federal government in Germany.
He examined, for example, the construction of motorways and major construction projects.
In addition, the Federal Audit Office drew on results from previous investigations.
The Supreme Control Office of the Czech Republic based its evaluations on test knowledge from 2008 to 2011, which included construction work in road construction, rail infrastructure construction, water construction, construction (hospitals, cultural buildings, university buildings, etc.) and other construction areas in the Czech Republic.
The awarding of federal public contracts in Germany is carried out predominantly by the building administrations of the federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the State Building Administration is centrally responsible for the procurement of transport infrastructure.
In the construction sector, the awards are carried out decentrally by those bodies that use the state budget.
In both countries, freelance workers are also involved in some areas of procurement procedures.
When comparing the evaluations, differences in procurement law and the market structure for construction services in both countries must be taken into account.
Development of public procurement law in both countries
In Germany, the implementation of EU-wide procurement procedures is laid down in laws and regulations.
Procurement procedures limited to the national sector are governed by budgetary law and the administrative rules that are based on it.
In addition, for both EU-wide and national awards, many complementary individual schemes are provided for by internal administrative provisions.
Such as the so-called "public procurement manuals" of the federal government, in which the legal requirements are supplemented or further formulated in accordance with the procurement law.
In the Czech Republic, the procurement procedure is governed exclusively by the public procurement law and other statutory provisions, which apply both above and below the EU thresholds.
The public procurement law was significantly amended in 2012.
The new rules increased transparency in the use of public funds, allowed greater competition and limited the opportunities for corruption in the procurement process.
Broad outlines of public procurement law in both countries
In both countries, the open procedure, the non-open procedure and the negotiation procedure must be applied to EU-wide contracts.
In Germany, the measures below the EU threshold are to be applied to the national types of contracts (public tender, limited tender, hands-free award), which are broadly in line with the aforementioned EU-wide types of contracts.
Public procurement law in Germany is characterised by the principle of the primacy of the open procedure (for contracts to be carried out across the EU) and the public tender (for national contracts).
In the open procedure and in the public tender process, any interested company can make an offer.
Another key feature of German public procurement law is the promotion of small and medium-sized enterprises.
This is mainly due to the division of an overall construction measure into specialist and partial units.
The individual award of these lots is intended to enable as many companies as possible to participate in the competition.
Both of the above-mentioned features of German public procurement law are proven tools for achieving economic results.
In Germany, there are over 330,000 construction companies with 1.9 million employees.
In the Czech Republic, the EU-wide procurement procedures are also applicable to construction projects below the EU threshold.
An exception is the simplified procedure, which allows a less stringent procedure to be applied below the thresholds and under certain conditions.
Czech public procurement law, in line with EU law, provides for contracts to be concluded if competition is guaranteed and a favourable price is achieved.
The current legal provisions in the Czech Republic allow the contracting authorities to choose between open and non-open procedures.
There are over 85,000 construction companies in the Czech Republic, of which about 1,900 are companies with 20 or more employees.
