Summary of the results of the parallel tests
The Supreme Audit Office of the Czech Republic (NKÚ) and the Federal Audit Office of the Federal Republic of Germany (BRH) have carried out parallel audits in their countries for the award of construction services across the EU and for the prevention of corruption.
In this context, the working groups of both auditors compared the relevant legal bases and administrative requirements in the Czech Republic and Germany, as well as the results of their parallel audits, which they carried out in particular in the areas of construction and road construction.
They found that:
The EU directives on the award of construction services by public contractors have been transposed into national law in both the Czech Republic and Germany (paragraphs 1 and 3.1).
In addition to the EU requirements, corruption prevention is also served by the procurement regulations of both countries, which differ in part in their priorities and in their details (No. 3.2).
In both countries, a key requirement for the procurement documents is that they must contain all the information needed to make an appropriate offer.
The performance descriptions must be neutral and must not be subject to anti-competitive requirements.
In Germany, the procurement documents have largely complied with these requirements.
In the Czech Republic, it is still a problem to determine the subject of the order sufficiently.
In Germany, construction services can be divided into lots in order to promote competition.
According to the findings of the BRH, this requirement was largely implemented in Germany.
In its audits, the NKÚ found, in particular in the field of road construction, that the award of extensive services without lots or with very large lots could affect competition and lead to a restriction on only a few large companies.
Narrowing the market potential can lead to significant cost increases and risk price or other collusion.
Under the provisions of both countries, the contracting authorities can, under certain conditions, agree in principle with the companies already contracted additional or amended services, which will prove necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (No. 4.1).
The respective benchmarks for determining the type of award were mostly followed in both countries.
According to the regulations of the Czech Republic, the contracting authorities are free to choose between open and non-open procedures.
In Germany, on the other hand, the legal and budgetary primacy of the open procedure applies to EU-wide awards and public tenders, which are in line with the open procedure for national awards.
This will allow more companies to make offers.
This reduces the risk of corruption, makes price agreements between bidders more difficult and leads to the most economic results.
In the case of construction projects, whose estimated total contract values reached or exceeded the EU threshold, the audited building authorities generally awarded construction services across Europe.
The true value of the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
In Germany, cost databases are used to determine the cost of public works, in particular in construction.
These are based on the evaluations of completed construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, a database is used in the field of road construction, but it is not yet an effective tool (No. 4.2).
In the case of construction services to be awarded across Europe, preliminary information and announcements must be published, which should strengthen competition by enabling interested companies to adjust to the planned contracts at an early stage.
The audited building authorities generally complied with this requirement.
In individual cases, incorrect information, incorrect applications or lack of controls may have affected competition (No. 4.3).
The selection of candidates for participation in non-public procurement procedures is particularly susceptible to manipulation.
Under EU law, the number of applicants invited must be sufficiently high to ensure genuine competition.
The selection criteria must be objective, must not discriminate and must be disclosed beforehand.
In addition to the requirements of the EU, the contracting authorities in both countries should, as often as possible, switch among the companies to be invited when selecting candidates.
In order to counter the risk of manipulation, there are sometimes very detailed guidelines in Germany.
In some cases, the audited administrations did not take these requirements into account.
In the Czech Republic, the decisions on the selection of candidates were not always comprehensible (No. 4.4).
In both countries, it is in the interest of equal competition to ensure that companies interested in bidding receive the same information during the bidding phase.
A contact between these companies and with freelancers involved in the creation of the service description is to be avoided as far as possible in order to avoid anti-competitive agreements.
The corresponding regulations in Germany are more extensive than in the Czech Republic.
The audited building authorities in Germany did not comply with these requirements in part (No. 4.5).
The opening up of the bids in both countries must take into account in particular the multi-eye principle and the principle of transparency.
The requirements for labelling, documentation, custody and secrecy of the offers are intended to narrow the scope for manipulation and are particularly well defined in Germany.
The tests in both countries yielded few complaints (No. 4.6).
In both countries, the examination and evaluation of the offers are determined by guidelines for the organisation of construction and execution.
The regulations in Germany are more comprehensive, but have not been consistently observed by the audited contracting authorities.
For example, tendering offices handed over offers for testing to third parties without first looking through the offers and sufficiently documenting any abnormalities.
The offers were thus insufficiently protected against subsequent manipulation (No. 4.7).
At the conclusion of the EU-wide procurement procedures, the companies involved in the competition will be informed of the proposed contract before the award of the contract.
This possibility of legal protection also has a preventive function against corrupt behaviour.
The Czech Republic also provides for a judicial review of non-EU procurement procedures.
Only in a few cases did the contracting authorities not comply with the prescribed deadlines when issuing orders, or deviated from the bidders' offer in terms of content (No. 4.8).
The documentation of the procurement procedures was not always complete or comprehensible to the audited building authorities in both countries.
In this respect, the EU-wide transparency requirement was not sufficiently implemented in the procurement notices of some procedures.
Some of the deficiencies identified also reduced the anti-corruption function of the documentation.
The public authorities in both countries largely complied with their reporting and reporting obligations (No. 4.9).
Foundations of EU public procurement law and corruption prevention
EU public procurement law
In order to ensure unrestricted competition within the European Union with the free movement of services and goods, the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union adopted, among other things, the Procurement Coordination and Appeal Directives, which had to be transposed into national law by the 8 Member States.
The general tendering principles of the European Union are, in particular, that of competition, equal treatment and non-discrimination, as well as transparency.
In order to achieve these objectives, the Procurement Coordination Directive sets out specific rules for construction projects to be forgiven across the EU.
In order to do so, their expected order totals must reach or exceed the current amount of 5,000,000 euros.
The rules relate in particular to the content of the award documents, the publication of certain information before, during and after the award, the adherence to deadlines, including the receipt of the offers, the documentation of the award procedure, the requirements that can be placed on the qualifications of the applicants and the Appeal Directive forms the basis for the legal protection of the applicants and bidders.
In the event of possible breaches of public procurement law, the companies concerned can have the decisions of the contracting authorities reviewed in review procedures.
Both the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have transposed the directives of the European Union into national law.
Prevention of corruption
The importance of preventing corruption
In both countries, there is no legal definition of the concept of corruption.
In general, corruption is the abuse of a position of trust for the private benefit,
This is usually caused by the beneficiaries of these decisions.
Corruption can hamper competition and cause significant economic damage.
It is estimated that the global cost of corruption is 5% of the world's economic output.
In the European Union, the amount of these costs is estimated at 1%.
In the case of public contractors, anti-competitive agreements or unfair practices can call into question confidence in the integrity and functioning of the administration.
Preventing corruption is therefore one of the basic tasks of public authorities.
In doing so, they will have to review the structure and execution of their administrations in areas that are particularly vulnerable to corruption in order to take appropriate safeguards against corruption.
Preventative measures and effective controls can significantly reduce the vulnerability of decision-making processes to corrupt abuse.
The award of public works services is generally regarded as a particularly corruption-prone area of work.
Anti-corruption measures
In Germany, corruption - in particular bribery and bribery, as well as prejudice and approval - is prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
In order to prevent corruption, the Federal Government has issued a guideline and recommendations on the prevention of corruption in the Federal Administration. In addition to the risk analysis, the following principles must be observed for the procurement sector: Priority of public tenders and open procedures, the principle of transparency and transparency, the fundamental separation of planning, awarding and settlement, precise and complete documentation of procurement procedures.
In addition, other anti-corruption provisions have been incorporated into the public procurement rules.
For example, in 2011, the Federal Ministry responsible for awarding contracts in the area of federal highways introduced an electronically assisted control system.
The award data - such as the estimated costs and the amount of orders - as well as information on the freelancers involved will be collected across the board and evaluated for abnormalities.
In the Czech Republic, corruption is also prosecuted under criminal and labour law.
The legal requirements of transparency and equal treatment of bidders, as well as the prohibition of all discrimination, are the most important bases for preventing corruption.
For public procurement, the Czech government has set out anti-corruption measures in a strategy paper on the fight against corruption for the years 2011 to 2012 and updated them for the years 2013 to 2014.
Some of the measures recommended in it have already been transposed into national public procurement law and related administrative provisions 14.
The new legislation essentially includes the following provisions: Lowering the thresholds for smaller contracts, requiring the contracting authority to notify the contracts beforehand, including naming the reasons for the tender, prohibiting the restriction of the number of bidders in non-open procedures, and thus abolishing the possibility of bidding through lottery procedures, introducing the obligation to publish the contract documents and all annexes, introducing the obligation to publish the actual price and the list of subcontractors.
Audit results on the different stages of the procurement process
Award documents
The tender documents must contain all the information the bidders need to make an appropriate offer.
In particular, the award documents must allow for an accurate calculation.
In doing so, the bidders must not be given risks that cannot be calculated for them.
The award documents consist in particular of the performance description and the terms of the contract.
In addition, they contain the requirements for proving the qualification (suitability) of the bidders as well as the criteria that determine the selection of the most economical offer.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
The requirements of EU law on procurement documents are in particular addressed to technical specifications.
These must be equally accessible to all bidders and should limit competition as little as possible.
The performance description must be basically product-neutral.
Therefore, information on products or manufacturers as part of the performance description is only permitted under strict conditions.
Avoiding anti-competitive requirements in the procurement documents is also a fundamental principle of preventing corruption.
In addition, unclear or incorrect information in the award documents must be avoided, as they open up scope for speculation in the preparation of the offers and for manipulation in their valuation.
German and Czech public procurement rules
The same or similar regulations in both countries have transposed the EU's technical specifications requirements into national law.
The services are basically product-neutral without any factory specifications.
In the performance descriptions, the individual performances must normally be subdivided into performance units with specific quantities.
Prices are to be agreed on the basis of performance units (e.g. Euro per m ² or per piece).
Only in exceptional cases can services be defined by functional targets.
In any case, the performance descriptions must be complete and unambiguous.
They must contain precise quantities and must not include services where it is not clear whether they are needed.
Compensation based on lump sums or on time expenditure should be avoided as far as possible.
These provisions are intended to prevent speculation and manipulation based on unspecified specifications in the procurement documents.
The performance descriptions must allow bidders to create their offers safely and without extensive preparatory work.
The tender will not be made public until the tender documents have been finalised.
Divergent rules
There is no obligation to tender for construction services in lots in the Czech Republic.
If it is possible according to the type of service to be commissioned, the public procurement offices can divide construction services into several lots.
In Germany, construction services are basically divided into lots, separated by quantity (partial) and / or by type or subject matter (unskilled).
The aim is to enable small and medium-sized enterprises to participate in the competition, to increase the number of potential suppliers and to make price agreements more difficult.
This type of award is generally considered the most economical.
In the Czech Republic, evaluation criteria must be specified in the procurement documents, both in the EU-wide and in the national procedures.
The aim is to ensure that applicants are fully and conclusively aware of the criteria for evaluating their offers.
In Germany, the specification of valuation criteria in EU-wide announcements, but at the latest in the procurement documents, is only required in EU-wide procurement procedures.
In the case of national procurement procedures, the evaluation criteria must only be set out in an internal administrative award notice.
Procurement documents drawn up by authorised freelancers may not contain any references to these offices or involved planners or reviewers in Germany in the construction and some road construction administrations.
This is to prevent individual companies from gaining additional information or other undue competitive advantages without the client's knowledge of the contact with these freelancers.
This is also why freelancers are not allowed to send award documents or interpret planning documents for inspection.
The contact person for the companies is the client alone.
There is currently no regulation in the Czech Republic.
Additional or modified services, which prove to be necessary after the conclusion of the original contract (supplements), are almost always required for large construction projects.
In both countries, the legal provisions allow, to a certain extent, the awarding of contracts to the already contracted company, without the need for a public procurement procedure.
According to EU regulations and German regulations, the remuneration of supplementary benefits must not exceed half of the main order.
In addition, the additional services must not be separated from the main order without significant disadvantages or must be absolutely necessary.
In the Czech Republic, a closer limit of 20% applies to the award without public notice.
However, this may increase the risk of delayed completion of the construction project or the need to involve an additional contractor in the construction work already underway.
If supplementary services are also transferred to the already contracted company, an arbitrary price increase for these services by the contractor is generally not possible under the regulations in Germany.
In determining the remuneration for the additional services, it should be based on the agreed prices and the basis of the price determination of the order already awarded.
In addition to supplementary services, there may also be a reduction in the scope of services.
In the Czech Republic, small amounts cannot be charged with additional supplementary services.
