When building a large library building, the performance description of the interior design did not include product quality requirements.
As a result of these missing specifications, some subcontractors built overpriced and unreasonably high quality equipment.
Loose and suitability criteria
In the Czech Republic, the division of construction activities into partial or partial contracts is not mandatory.
An examination of the three large sections of the construction of a motorway ring revealed that if selected parts were to be allocated separately, savings of up to 31.6 million euros would have been possible at a total cost of 620.3 million euros.
For example, in six different buildings alone, which were the subject of a single contract, 2.5 million euros (25%) could have been saved in the case of a separate award.
If the construction of 20 bridges were to be allocated separately, savings of 11.5 million euros (25%) would have been possible compared to a total allocation.
When it came to the award of construction services in road construction, the central contracting authority set out very extensive reference requirements as suitability criteria.
In the construction of part of a motorway, the contracting authority required bidders in an open process to demonstrate, among other things, at least three road construction projects carried out, each worth 28 million euros over the last five years.
In the Czech Republic, no more than nine providers met these requirements.
The public procurement of another part of a motorway included six separate construction projects, in which the contracting authority had set an annual construction volume of at least €480 million over the last three years as a criterion of suitability for the companies.
Two thirds of the funds raised for road construction projects in 2008 and 2009 (i.e. 2.5 billion euros out of a total of 3.7 billion euros) came from commissions from a total of five companies that carried out the contracts alone or as a working group.
In 46 procurement procedures with an order volume of 528 million euros, only two or even just one bidder made an offer.
The NKÚ showed that a narrowing of the market potential could lead to significant cost increases.
Additional services
In the case of the construction of a car bypass, the contracting authority did not apply any of the statutory procedures to the award of additional services in two cases, nor did it enter into written contracts for the additional services.
Due to unclear quantity and quality requirements, submissions in the first case amounted to up to 63.7 million euros (net) and in the second case up to 165.4 million euros (net), which increased the respective order volume by 21% and 91% respectively.
