Other findings
Based on a sampling of construction projects, the NKÚ found that the average cost of building a four-lane motorway kilometre in the Czech Republic is up to 14.6 million euros.
In Deuschland, on the other hand, the average cost of a four-lane motorway kilometre is up to 10.4 million euros, according to an analysis of long-term data from the Federal Ministry of Building and Construction.
This comparison suggests that motorway construction in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in Germany.
Summary findings
The basic rules on procurement documents are broadly consistent in both countries and take into account the EU requirements.
They serve both comprehensive and fair competition and corruption prevention.
For example, the requirement for the sufficient determination of performance descriptions should enable bidders to calculate and create their offers in an appropriate manner.
Protect the client from additional services to be agreed upon afterwards and also reduce the scope for speculation.
In Germany, the common basic requirements for the procurement documents are supplemented by regulations aimed at further reducing restrictions on competition and opportunities for manipulation.
In the Czech Republic, there are no requirements to this extent, but transparency is increased by publishing the evaluation criteria for non-EU-wide procurement procedures.
The requirements for describing performance have largely been met in both countries.
In some cases, however, deviations had to be objected to, which may also have led to restrictions on competition.
The existing bid for the formation of lots in Germany promotes competition and leads to economic results.
In the Czech Republic, according to the audit findings of the NKÚ, the awarding of extensive services without lots or with very large lots can result in restrictions on the supplier field to only a few large companies.
The extensive reference requirements for road construction in the Czech Republic have meant that public contracts are awarded only to a narrow circle of suppliers and that smaller and medium-sized enterprises are not allowed to compete.
Also, a limited number of competitors often lead to higher prices and increase the risk of price or other collusion.
When awarding and remunerating additional or modified services, the regulatory approaches in both countries differ.
According to EU and German regulations, supplementary services with a value of up to half of the main contract can be awarded with public notice under certain conditions without procurement procedures.
In the Czech Republic, there is a narrower limit of 20%, up to which additional services can be awarded to the original contractor in the negotiation process without notice.
