Define the type of award and take into account the EU threshold
By determining the type of award, the client determines the extent of the number of companies participating in the competition.
It can leave the circle of potential candidates and bidders largely unrestricted, for example by choosing an open procedure, or by imposing non-public procurement procedures.
Europe-wide procurement procedures must be applied to construction projects where a threshold set by the EU is reached or exceeded.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
When choosing the type of award, the contracting authority must take into account, in particular, the European legal requirements for competition and transparency.
If the estimated total contract value of the construction services of a project is at or above the EU threshold of currently 5,000,000 euros, construction services are generally to be awarded across Europe in accordance with open or non-open procedures.
In exceptional cases, negotiation procedures or competitive dialogue are also possible.
In the case of construction projects that reach or exceed the EU threshold, the contracting authority may deviate to a limited extent from the principle of Europe-wide procurement and award works in national procurement procedures, provided that the estimated contract value of the respective lot is less than 1,000,000 euros and the sum of these lots does not exceed 20% of the estimated total contract value of all construction contracts.
A single construction project must not be divided into individual measures without a compelling reason, or deliberately valued at too low a cost, in order to avoid the obligation to award construction services across Europe as a matter of principle.
As restrictions on competition significantly increase the risk of manipulation, the choice of the type of award is of great importance in preventing corruption.
The detailed justification of the chosen type of award as well as the examination of the application obligation of the EU procurement rules are important elements of the documentation of the award procedure.
German and Czech public procurement rules
Same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed EU rules on procurement procedures and thresholds into national law.
Divergent rules
The Czech Republic has also transferred the fundamental equivalence of open and non-open procedures contained in the EU directive to its construction contracts, which are not subject to EU requirements.
There is freedom of choice between the open and the non-open procedure, without the decision having to be doctored or substantiated, while other procedures are only possible under certain legally defined conditions.
In Germany, on the other hand, the open procedure, or - in the case of national awards - the public tender procedure, in principle, takes precedence, as defined by budgetary and public procurement law and by the anti-corruption guidelines.
Other types of tendering - such as the non-open procedure or the limited tendering procedure - are only possible in exceptional cases, which are finalised in the procurement law.
The existence of an exceptional case must be substantiated and documented in a comprehensible manner.
The principle of the primacy of the open procedure or the public tender is to ensure that competition is as unrestricted as possible, to exclude the possibility of manipulation by specifying certain bidders and to make possible price agreements between bidders more difficult.
The principle of public tendering is a key element in preventing corruption in Germany.
The true value of the expected value of the contract is an essential basis for choosing the right type of contract.
Construction services in Germany can rely on planning and cost databases from public administrations and other organisations to determine the expected costs in the area of public construction.
These databases are based on evaluations of completed construction projects. Among other things, the databases contain cost indicators for building categories, use units, components or individual construction services.
On the basis of such cost parameters, the expected order value of a planned project or construction work to be awarded can be determined.
In Germany, the corresponding cost databases for road construction have only been provided by a number of building authorities.
However, a nationwide introduction for all road construction administrations is planned.
Procurement offices in the Czech Republic cannot rely on central databases or average price surveys of comparable construction projects to determine the estimated cost of construction services.
On the contrary, in most cases, the cost investigations are based on estimates of the funding body or are based on the amount of funds made available to the construction service.
Measures to standardise cost assessment procedures are still in their infancy.
The relevant ministries were commissioned to create a database for standardised building materials and materials as part of the anti-corruption plan for 2011-2012.
