In a cross-sectional investigation, based on more than 16,000 tendering procedures, the BRH found that non-public tenders have significant competitive disadvantages over open procedures and public tenders and increase the risk of manipulation and corruption.
In construction, more than twice as many bids were submitted for public tenders as for limited tenders and almost three times as many bids as for hands-free tenders.
The investigation also found that, on average, bidding prices for limited tenders and hands-free tenders were 6% and 10% higher than for public tenders.
Parallel investigations by the Federal Ministry of Buildings and a National Audit Office confirmed the economic differences between public and non-public tenders.
As a result of its research into economic efficiency, the Federal Ministry of Building and Construction even found that there were twice as many differences between public and non-public procurement procedures.
Taking into account the EU threshold
In the case of the construction projects, for which they had identified a projected total contract amount of more than 5,000,000 euros, the audited contracting authorities usually set out procurement plans in which they set out the construction services to be awarded in accordance with EU and national procurement procedures.
According to the procurement plans, this meant that more than 80% of construction services were to be awarded across the EU.
It was impossible to see how the commitment to EU-wide contracts could be circumvented by overly low cost estimates.
However, partly as a result of incorrect calculations, the minimum proportion of EU procurement procedures actually fell.
During the construction process, a number of tendering offices improperly changed the terms of their tendering plans.
They did not justify these changes and did not demonstrate that the minimum proportion of EU-wide procurement procedures was still being complied with.
For most of the construction measures audited, the proportion of EU-wide contracts was usually lower than foreseen under the procurement plan, according to the settlement results.
