Review and evaluation of offers
The client must examine and evaluate the offers available at the opening date.
In doing so, he has to determine the offer for the award of the award, which best meets the requirements according to the award criteria.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
The EU's guidelines provide for a multi-stage procedure:
First of all, the suitability of the bidders has to be determined.
Bidders must be economically and financially efficient and have the necessary professional and technical expertise.
Companies that are legally convicted of bribery or fraud, for example, must be excluded from participating in the award procedure.
The bids of the non-excluded bidders must be examined in a computational, technical and economic manner and evaluated on the basis of the award criteria previously announced.
The client has to determine the most economically advantageous offer, and the client has to examine offers with unusually low prices in particular.
The examination and evaluation of the offers is a particularly susceptible phase of the tendering process.
For example, bidders can be unjustifiably excluded or offers that do not meet the requirements can be left in competition.
By favouring or discriminating against bidders, the value result can be inadvertently impaired and thus prevented from finding the most economically advantageous offer.
The contracting authority must therefore take special precautions to ensure that the persons responsible for the audit and evaluation meet the requirements for integrity and expertise.
It must also ensure the transparency and traceability of the procedure and the decisions taken.
German and Czech public procurement rules
Same or similar rules
In line with EU requirements, bids in both countries must be examined and evaluated in multi-stage procedures.
The requirements for the suitability of the companies to be presented, as well as the award criteria to be taken into account in the assessment and their weighting, are set out in the notices or in the award documents and cannot be changed during the process.
After checking the bidding appropriation, the eligibility criteria may no longer be used when evaluating the bids.
The rating must be limited to the award criteria.
The submitted offers must first be formally examined immediately as to whether they are complete and whether they contain, for example, abnormalities that could indicate possible manipulation intentions.
If bidders are excluded from further examination and evaluation of their offers, they must be informed immediately.
If the valuation of the offers results in an unreasonably low price, the bidder must be given the opportunity to comment before a possible exclusion of his offer.
The decisions taken in the examination and evaluation of the offers are to be documented in a comprehensible manner.
Divergent rules
In Germany, the offers to be kept secret may only be made available to those directly responsible for processing them.
The review of the offers and the computational examination of the offers may only be carried out by the contracting authority.
It only has to employ staff who are not involved in the award decision or the implementation of the measure.
The performance of further examination and evaluation tasks is not specified.
If freelancers are entrusted with the examination and evaluation, they have to treat the offers confidentially.
They can only make proposals for the decisions to be taken by the contracting authorities.
In the Czech Republic, award committees are to be set up to examine and evaluate the offers.
The committees produce valuation reports with award proposals.
In the end, as in Germany, only the contracting authorities have to decide on the award of contracts.
If the proof or explanation required to submit an offer in Germany is only incomplete, the contracting authority must give the bidders the opportunity to submit the missing documents within six days.
Only if the documents are still not available after the expiry of the deadline can the offer be excluded from the valuation.
In the Czech Republic, it is at the discretion of the contracting authority whether it gives the bidders the opportunity to complete a lack of evidence or explanation.
If a bidder fails to do so, he must be excluded.
In Germany, in addition to the total price, the unit prices (prices for partial services) of the offers have to be examined.
If, due to the price structure of the offer, there are indications that prices for partial services are too low or too high, the bidder must be asked to clear up these ambiguities.
If he fails to do so, and if the contracting authority can provide proof of a miscalculation of prices, this offer is excluded.
This is to prevent bidders from speculating on significant changes in the volume of partial services when calculating their offer, which can lead to significant increases in the cost of construction projects.
In the Czech Republic, the total price is assessed, but not the appropriateness of the prices for partial services.
A mixed calculation cannot justify the exclusion of an offer.
Offers with unreasonably high or low prices may not be awarded in Germany.
If one or more offers fall short of the correct price determination of the client or the offer amounts of the other bidders by 10% or more, the bidders have to prove the correct calculation of their offers.
If they are unable to do so, the contracting authority can exclude the offers in question.
In the Czech Republic, the call for tenders can be rescinded after an audit of profitability, if only offers with unjustifiable prices are available at low prices.
In contrast to German public procurement law, for this reason, the contract cannot be refused for offers with prices significantly higher than the client's calculation.
If there is a suspicion of anti-competitive behaviour in Germany, the contracting authority must immediately report to its supervisory authority.
The Commission has to decide what measures to take and whether the antitrust authority or the public prosecutor's office should be informed.
The specialist supervisor at the top level, for example, also has to agree to more than 50,000 euros for construction work if the contract is to be awarded by hand, if a contract is not to be awarded for the lowest price or if the tender is to be cancelled.
There are no such regulations in the Czech Republic.
