In many cases, the discrepancies were only justified on a blanket basis, for example by references to changed market prices or increased material costs.
The building services said that it was difficult to identify and prove mixed-use calculations.
In the case of a public service tender, the offer price of the cheapest offer was 66% below the previously estimated value of these services.
Further calculations or investigations into the causes of this deviation were not documented.
In a briefing, the contracting authority found no evidence of price dumping by the then contracted company.
As a result, it remained unclear whether the estimated value was excessive or whether the offer price was too low.
Later, the client rated the contracted company as a "low-cost company" that could not maintain quality or deadlines.
In another call for tenders, a construction service awarded the contract to an offer whose price was 35% higher than the value of the cost calculation.
It did not lift the call for tenders, citing the non-factual reason that this company could be closed to a reasonable calculation.
Suspicion of irregularities
There have been two cases of irregularities in an audited building administration, both of which have been reported to the supervisor level.
In one of the cases, the calculation of two bidders in a tender was identical, so that the contracting authority excluded both bids from the process.
When applying the other rules, the tests did not raise any significant objections.
NKÚ
Aptitude test
In many of the audited construction projects, including higher education, road construction and the expansion of the rail network, the contracting authorities did not exclude bidders from the process, even though they did not meet the requirements set out in the tender documents or could not prove their suitability to the required extent. On the other hand, in one case, a contracting authority could neither prove nor explain why it had excluded a bidder who had met the requirements.
Rating
When awarding construction services for a water treatment plant, the contracting authority did not take into account the given criteria for evaluating and evaluating the offers.
In the case of a construction project to expand the rail network, the award office did not determine the weighting of the evaluation criteria until the start of the evaluation.
In the case of road maintenance measures, the predetermined criterion of "shortening the construction phase" was misjudged in a procedure.
As a result, the shortening offered was not sufficiently taken into account by the second and third position bidders.
Documentation of the selection of offers
In three tendering procedures within the framework of housing development, the contracting authority did not document the criteria it applied and on what basis it had selected the successful bidder.
In the construction of a motorway, the contracting authority selected the companies for smaller orders up to 20,000 euros solely on the basis of telephone surveys on prices and delivery conditions.
Tests of this selection were not possible because the surveys were not documented.
Summary findings
The rules for testing and evaluating offers in both countries are in line with EU requirements.
However, with regard to the details of the procedure and the selection of the persons involved, the respective regulations differ.
In Germany, the procedure is more regulated than in the Czech Republic by detailed requirements, in particular for the implementation of the multi-eye principle and for the protection of offers.
The same applies to the specifications, on the basis of which the adequacy of the offered prices must be examined.
In both countries, some of the audited tendering procedures found that significant procedural steps in the examination and evaluation of tenders were not or were not sufficiently documented.
Without traceability and transparency of audit and evaluation decisions, however, possible manipulative interventions are encouraged.
A particularly serious deficiency was the handing over of all offers to third parties, without the contracting authority having previously sufficiently reviewed and documented the offers and thus protected them from possible manipulation in further proceedings.
If contracting authorities are to carry out tasks in the examination and evaluation of the offers by third parties, sufficient precautions and an increased amount of control are required to counter the increased risk of manipulation.
When assessing the adequacy of the prices, the audited services in Germany did not always make full use of the set instruments and did not adequately examine the price structure of the offers.
In the Czech Republic, complaints arose mainly in the aptitude test and in the application of the evaluation criteria.
Conclusion of the award procedure
After checking and evaluating the offers, the award procedure is completed by granting the contract or by cancelling the procedure.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention
In the case of EU-wide procurement procedures, all bidders must be informed in advance of the planned award decision.
The companies have the option to examine the intended award within 10 days, or for other means of communication within 15 days, in the event of information being provided electronically or by fax, and, if necessary, to initiate a review procedure.
A contract may not be concluded before the expiry of this information period.
