If a bidder requests a review within the information period, the conclusion of the contract is only possible after the final decision in the review process.
Companies can also have the award decision reviewed by an independent court as part of this review process.
The review procedure is designed to ensure the legal protection of companies and to encourage the client to comply with the procurement law throughout the procurement process.
In order to do this, he must sufficiently document the procedure.
German and Czech public procurement rules
Same or similar rules
Both countries have implemented EU rules on information and verification procedures.
In both countries, the contracting authority has to decide on the award of the contract.
However, it must not deviate arbitrarily from the result of a proper examination and evaluation of the offers.
The client is to place the order within the announced deadline,
Also because the bidders are no longer bound by their offers after the deadline.
In the case of open and non-open procedures or public and limited tenders, the client must not deviate from the content of the offer when concluding the contract.
The defeated bidders must be informed promptly of the award decision and the reasons for not taking their offers into account.
Tendering procedures may only be lifted under certain conditions, for example if the offer prices are excessive or the offers do not meet the requirements of the tender.
Divergent rules
In the Czech Republic, there is a 10-day or 15-day obligation to provide information and to wait before awarding the contract, even for construction services not to be awarded across Europe.
In Germany, these requirements apply only to EU-wide contracts.
In the case of the other proceedings in Germany, the bidders can only be informed of the award decision after the award has been awarded.
In the Czech Republic, a tendering procedure must be lifted if only one offer has been received or only one offer has been assessed.
In Germany, the contract must also be awarded in the case of only one valuable offer, provided that it complies with the terms of the tender and is economical.
Key exam results
BRH
In the case of the audited awards, there were only a few complaints at the conclusion of the award procedures.
In some cases, companies received letters of order for EU-wide contracts before the expiry of the information deadlines, which may lead to the ineffectiveness of the contract.
Also, according to open procedures, order letters contained content that deviated from the content of the offer in individual cases, such as changed dates.
In several cases, the clients did not comply with the award deadlines.
In an open procedure, a contracting authority therefore awarded the contract for the second cheapest offer, as a company with a 50% cheaper offer was no longer willing to carry out the services at the originally offered price after the end of the contract period.
NKÚ
In the case of a construction project in the higher education sector, the contracting authority deviated from the bidder's offer in terms of content in the contract.
In some contracts, for example in the construction of road maintenance, the construction of a motorway and a bypass road, the contracting authorities concluded the contracts after the expiry of the legal deadline.
When awarding construction services for the redevelopment of the former military site, the contracting authority only forwarded the notification of the award to all bidders after the expiry of the legal deadline.
Summary findings
Both countries have implemented the EU's requirements to complete the procurement process.
The legal protection of the defeated candidates or bidders will increase the tools for preventing corruption.
The scope of legal protection in Czech public procurement law is also extended to contracts below the EU thresholds.
In both countries, the deadlines for placing orders have been exceeded.
This can lead to economic disadvantages and increase the risk of manipulation.
In the future, the building authorities should avoid the shortcomings identified when concluding their tendering procedures.
Documentation, reporting and reporting obligations
The award procedures must be documented in a comprehensible manner during their individual stages with regard to the relevant findings and the reasons for the individual decisions.
In EU-wide procedures, the contracts awarded must be made public.
The order data is also recorded in an EU statistic.
Requirements of EU law and corruption prevention The documentation of procurement procedures implements a fundamental requirement of the EU-wide transparency offer.
A carefully and promptly produced documentation makes it possible to trace the award decisions.
In particular, it also serves the effective legal protection of bidders for contracts above the EU thresholds.
Proper documentation is also an essential part of preventing corruption, as the compulsion to explain procurement decisions in detail significantly reduces the scope for manipulation.
The notice of a contract awarded in an EU-wide procurement procedure must be sent to the Office for Official Publications of the EU within 48 days.
The Office publishes the notices in the Official Journal of the EU, which also implements the transparency requirement.
The contracting authorities also have to collect the essential data of their procurement procedures and report it to the EU Commission through the relevant national ministries.
On this basis, the European Commission draws up an annual EU statistics to provide an overview of the development of the internal market in construction services.
German and Czech public procurement rules
Same or similar rules
Both countries have fully transposed the EU's documentation and reporting requirements into national law.
The rules on documentation and reporting for EU statistics are broadly the same in both countries.
Divergent rules
In the Czech Republic, the obligation to publish contracts is not only limited to EU-wide contracts, but also extends to other procurement procedures.
The notice period is reduced to 15 days.
In Germany, in addition to EU-wide contracts, there is a duty to publish only in the case of limited tenders and in the case of hands-free contracts with value limits of 25,000 euros or 15,000 euros without VAT (so-called ex-post transparency).
Below these value limits and in the case of public tenders, only the companies involved in the competition procedure will receive information about the orders.
Key exam results
BRH
Documentation
A large number of the audited procurement procedures were not fully documented.
The award notices did not contain all the necessary information, such as the justification of product specifications or references to national regulations.
In a procurement procedure, the contracting authority did not explain why it awarded the contract to a company, although its offer did not include mandatory proof.
In a few cases, the documents of the contracting authorities did not contain all the evidence necessary for the documentation of the award procedure.
Announcements of orders
In some EU-wide procurement procedures, the contracting authorities failed to disclose the award of contracts.
In the case of further procurement procedures, there was no evidence that the contracting authorities had disclosed the contracts awarded.
Reporting and reporting obligations
The statistical records reviewed contained the minimum required information, which had been prepared and sent on time.
Ex-post transparency
In most cases, the audited building authorities published the contract data of the completed procurement procedures.
However, due to a transmission error, this data was not published by a building management company.
The building management only noticed this error after half a year,
As a result, the order data of the procurement procedures that had been completed up to then were not published.
