Summary evaluation and recommendations
Parallel audits by the NKÚ and the BRH have focused on two main areas that are essential in the Czech Republic and Germany for the award of construction services by public authorities: The application of EU procurement rules and the prevention of corruption.
The requirements of EU law allow cross-border competition to create a single European market.
Anti-corruption measures are not only designed to prevent or at least reduce corruption, but also to avert economic damage and a possible loss of confidence in the integrity of the state.
The audit expertise of the two auditors on the application of public procurement rules in both countries, as well as the comparison of these rules, reveal similarities and differences that can be helpful for both countries in developing their procurement law and its application.
Application of EU public procurement rules
The EU's requirements for the award of construction services have been transposed into national law by both countries.
Thus, in the Czech Republic and in Germany, there is an important common basis for awarding construction services and taking into account the essential bids of competition, the equal treatment of the companies involved and the transparency of procurement procedures.
The building authorities in both countries have in some cases been very supportive of these bids through further administrative regulations.
The Czech Republic has also largely transferred the requirements for the construction services to be awarded across the EU to its nationally regulated procurement procedures below the EU threshold.
However, the auditors' investigations have shown that the building services have not fully complied with the requirements of EU law in all areas.
The construction administration in Germany should continue to improve the quality of its procurement procedures in order to be able to resolve the complaints raised when implementing the EU requirements.
The tests in the Czech Republic have shown, in particular, dangers that affect the profitability of the contracts.
For example, incomplete performance descriptions necessitated additional services, which were often awarded in breach of legislation, and cost assessments were often inadequate, and excessive qualification requirements also reduced the number of potential bidders and, in particular, restricted competition in the transport sector.
Prevention of corruption
The investigation did not aim to uncover cases of corruption,
Also because the auditors do not have the tools to do so.
However, the auditors can examine the extent to which the administrations of both countries have taken precautions against corruption and manipulation in the awarding of works and how these requirements are applied.
Both countries have set different priorities for preventing corruption.
In particular, the German regulations provide for largely unrestricted competition, as well as transparency and controls as key elements of the prevention of corruption.
The Czech regulations are mainly aimed at increasing the transparency of procedures.
BRH
In Germany, general principles of corruption prevention apply, which must be applied by the entire federal administration.
These principles are also implemented in the specifications for the award of construction services and are geared towards their specific requirements.
In some cases, the relevant regulations set out very precisely how the bids to prevent corruption should be taken into account in the course of the award procedures and in the selection of the persons involved.
According to the BRH, in particular, the primacy of the principle of open procedure or public tendering is an appropriate tool to significantly reduce the risk of corruption in the awarding of construction services, while restrictions on competition increase the risk of manipulation.
Risk analyses and adequate controls (especially the multi-eye principle), the requirements for transparency and documentation of procurement procedures and various organisational measures are also effective measures to prevent corruption and manipulation.
The BRH therefore does not see any need for fundamental changes to the relevant requirements of the administrations in the award of construction services.
The rules for preventing corruption are largely taken into account in practice.
The shortcomings identified in some areas have highlighted shortcomings in the implementation of some of the requirements.
The building authorities should continue to train their employees on the anti-corruption guidelines and make them even more aware of this issue.
A significant part of the complaints related to tasks that the building authorities had delegated to freelance workers.
However, without controls and adequate safeguards, the risk of abuse increases when delegating tasks.
Therefore, tasks at risk of manipulation and corruption should only be entrusted to third parties if the administration can ensure a sufficient level of protection against unlawful interference.
NKÚ
The Czech Republic has adopted a strategy against corruption at government level, in which public procurement is the most important component.
The procurement law and its implementing provisions have been substantially amended.
The NKÚ audits took place during the implementation of this strategy.
The strategy adopted and the new legal provisions are likely to be effective improvement measures, as the contracting authorities will have to justify the cost-effectiveness of the orders, the calculation of the expected prices, the adequacy of the qualification requirements, the essential assessment criteria and the nature of the evaluations, and properly document and publish all these aspects.
Recommendations
The NKÚ and the BRH are generally positive about the implementation of the EU guidelines.
The widespread acceptance in practice has confirmed that the EU's bids for competition, equal treatment and transparency are an appropriate basis for the award of construction services within the European Union.
The supranational model implemented in the European Union can also serve as a basis for similar projects to enable and promote cross-border competition.
In view of the enormous material and ideal potential for damage caused by manipulation and corruption in the awarding of construction services, both auditors are calling on the building authorities in their countries to continue and, if necessary, improve their measures against corruption and manipulation.
In particular, the organisation and procedures of procurement procedures should be continuously investigated for weaknesses and risks in order to identify the need for action and to take appropriate countermeasures.
The comparison of procurement practices in both countries suggests that the share of open procedures in the Czech Republic should be increased, as open procedures offer a wider scope for competition and can significantly reduce the risk of corruption.
In addition, a greater division of construction services into lots can have a favourable effect on supply prices, provided it achieves greater competition with a higher number of bidders.
Ensuring the correct implementation of procurement procedures is an essential basis for efficient contracting by public authorities.
In Germany, the procurement procedures are carried out by the specialised building services, whereas in the Czech Republic, these tasks - with the exception of transport projects - are carried out by the departments themselves or contractors appointed by them.
The auditors of both countries are anxious, even after the completion of their joint project, to develop the relevant findings and, if necessary, to bring them to the parliament and government of their country.
Both auditors are also convinced that the principles of public procurement law set out in this report and its implementation are also of interest at the international level of the International Organization of Supreme Audit Institutions (INTOSAI), because the principles and findings outlined are of general importance in order to effectively counter corruption and to ensure the economic award of construction services in a well-functioning and fair competition.
